  "prompt": "If nails and hair are basically dead cells, how come they grow?",
  "response": "Hair and nails appear to \"grow\" because new cells are constantly being produced at the base of the hair follicle or nail matrix, even though the visible parts of hair and nails are indeed made of dead cells. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. Hair growth:\n- Hair grows from the hair follicle at the base of the hair shaft\n- Living cells in the follicle divide and push older cells upward\n- As these cells move up, they die and become keratinized\n- The dead, hardened cells form the hair shaft we see\n\n2. Nail growth:\n- Nails grow from the nail matrix, located under the cuticle\n- New cells are continuously produced at the matrix\n- As new cells form, they push older cells forward\n- These cells die and become compacted, forming the hard nail plate\n- The visible part of the nail is made of these dead, compacted cells\n\nSo while the visible parts of hair and nails are technically dead, growth occurs through continuous cell production at the base. This process is similar to how skin cells are constantly replaced, with new cells pushing older ones outward.\n\nThe growth is driven by cell division in the living tissue beneath the surface, creating the illusion of ongoing growth of what appears to be a \"dead\" structure.",
